      <hedline>
        <hl1>Human Habits Must Change</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Nancy Dickeman letter on June 25 article on environmental threat to spruce forest in Kenai, Alaska, urges move away from fossil fuels and toward wind and solar power</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The specter of climate change takes on new dimensions of urgency when one ponders the stricken forests in Kenai, Alaska (''On Hot Trail of Tiny Killer,'' June 25).</p>
        <p>Whether climate change is partly or fully implicated in this forest's decimation is of less consequence than the broader picture: climate change is taking an irrevocable and irrefutable toll.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The specter of climate change takes on new dimensions of urgency when one ponders the stricken forests in Kenai, Alaska (''On Hot Trail of Tiny Killer,'' June 25).</p>
        <p>Whether climate change is partly or fully implicated in this forest's decimation is of less consequence than the broader picture: climate change is taking an irrevocable and irrefutable toll.</p>
        <p>A byproduct of human activity -- the burning of fossil fuels -- climate change also represents a crisis that we have the power to ameliorate, if only we would. Fuel conservation and the development and use of wind and solar power are steps we must take now.</p>
        <p>The death of a beautiful stand of spruce shows that our actions have tangible effects. It also provides an opportunity to take the fork in the road needed to save forests and stop environmental ravages.</p>
        <p>NANCY DICKEMAN  Seattle</p>
      </block>
